This implementation seems idiotic to me.  Having focus items varying the percentage of focus seems like a much cleaner, simpler, and less artificial solution.  Newbie items could have stuff like 1-2% focus to keep them happy, 40's items could have focus around 25% (a la FBSS), low 50's stuff could have focus around 30% (RBG), high 50's stuff could be 35%, and uber stuff could be 40%.  Maybe those percentages all need to be scaled down because the different types of focus effects &quot;stack&quot;, but the idea is clear.  Then again, that would be intelligent implementation, something Verant certainly isn't known for. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uwyvernwyrmsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wyvern Wyrmsong</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 158<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/7/02 9:40:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3394.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: VI needs to withdraw head from ass</span><hr size=1> Let me clarify what I am saying above.<br>
<br>
#1 The numbers are for illustration only, I know nothing about damage to mana ratios.<br>
<br>
If some DD spell under level 44 does 1 damage/10 mana, and suddenly with Focus2 it does 1damage/7 mana, is it more efficient than the 44+ spell that does 1 damage / 8 mana that is not affected by Focus 2?  No.  I do not have hard numbers, but I imagine for the 44-50something range players this scenario would exist for a while.  <br>
<br>
By the time someone is level 60 they probably have spells that do 1 damage / &lt; 7 mana without any focus at all, but that is a hint to upgrade your gear at that level if you want the added effect of Focus items at that level.  Sorry that you cannot go solo or experience group that focus gear you want at level 60.  And from that list above, some of the Focus 3 items are still readily available to smaller groups/raids, etc.<br>
 <br>
#2 I may not have made this clear above either, and number values are irrelevant except as relative comparisons: <br>
<br>
A level 20 melee wearing no haste does X damage.<br>
A level 20 melee wearing FBSS at 22% haste does X + 22% damage.<br>
A level 20 melee wearing CoF at 36% does X + 22% damage.<br>
<br>
Why?  Because there is a maximum haste cap that raises with levels.  Someone under level 60 cannot achieve 100% haste, even if they have spells and equipment that would give a level 60 100% haste.  So even though the level 20 above with the CoF has a haste *potential* of X + 36%, he cannot get the full haste because it is capped lower.<br>
<br>
Now, perhaps solo with no spell haste, this cap is not reached by items alone, I do not really have haste parse numbers by level to give hard figures, but I know the cap exists and rises with level, and that is my point.<br>
<br>
Therefore, a level 20 with a FBSS haste and a level 20 with CoF haste both have the same actual haste due to a lower maximum haste cap determined by level.  <br>
<br>
So too, a level 20 caster with Focus I item gets exactly the same benefit as a level 20 caster with the Focus III item.<br>
<br>
VI decided it did not want level 20's with 100% haste, by giving them a level based maximum haste, regardless of spells or haste equipment.  They (VI) seem to have decided they also did not want level 20 casters to use for example 30% less mana per cast or 30% more DD per cast with a Focus III item, instead of a 20% with Focus II or 10% with a Focus I item.  Instead they decided to limit the focus effect (which stays the same the percentage) by what spell levels are affected, and only allow the effect to apply to higher spells with higher focus items.<br>
<br>
And if you are still convinced this is some sort of Uber-cism against you, with The Man (VI) holding you down, remember anyone can access many of these same abilities if a mage is around, or through AA abilities which are NOT restricted to uber players only.<br>
<br>
I like focus items for casters, and agree they should be limited in access just like the best gear is limited.  Hell, bards do not even get any focus benefits and I support this move. <p>Wyvern Wyrmsong <br>
